According to the antient constitution of the Court of Exchequer‚ seats at the third table were appropriated to two officers, whose duty it was to enter on record, each for himself} the returns made into the court in each successive year by the sheriffs of the counties who acted as the King’s bailiffs, and, occasionally, by other persons who had to account to the King in his Exchequer for any portion of the royal revenue.
